.TH MBR88 5 "2026" "MBR88 v0.2" "File Formats"
.\"
.\" -------------------------------------------------------------------------
.SH NAME
.\"
MBR88 \- binary format of the traditional Master Boot Record and MBR88 extensions
.\"
.\" -------------------------------------------------------------------------
.SH DESCRIPTION
.\"
This page documents the on-disk binary format of the 512-byte Master Boot
Record as used by
.BR MBR88 .
It covers the standard MBR fields present on all traditional
MBR-partitioned disks, plus the
.B MBR88
extensions.
Fields specific to
.B MBR88
are marked
.BR [MBR88] .
.PP
The MBR partition table format is compatible with operating systems from
MS-DOS 2.0 (1983) through current Linux kernels, and with everything
in between that matters: FreeDOS, DR-DOS, OS/2, Windows through at least
Windows 10, and ELKS.
.B MBR88
boot records have been tested on FreeDOS and ELKS; the partition table
itself is read correctly by anything that speaks traditional MBR.
.PP
The MBR format was introduced with IBM PC DOS\ 2.0 in 1983, designed for
the original IBM PC XT.
In those 512 bytes live the boot code, the four-entry partition table,
and a handful of compatibility fields that accreted over the years as
various operating systems quietly decided that some of that unused space
was theirs now.
.B MBR88
continues this proud tradition by adding a boot menu and partition labels
to the bytes that generic DOS loaders leave as zeros.
.\"
.\" -------------------------------------------------------------------------
.SH MEMORY MAP
.\"
.TS
l l l .
\fBOffset\fR	\fBSize\fR	\fBDescription\fR
0x000	3	Jump instruction to boot code entry point
0x003	438	Boot code region  (see below)
0x1B0	1	[MBR88] Code slack byte (reserved, 0x00)
0x1B1	1	[MBR88] Cassini byte (0xD9)
0x1B2	5	[MBR88] Signature: ASCII \fBmbr88\fR
0x1B7	1	[MBR88] Version byte
0x1B8	4	Disk ID (32-bit little-endian)
0x1BC	2	Write-protect flag
0x1BE	64	Partition table (4 \(mu 16 bytes)
0x1FE	2	Boot signature 0x55 0xAA
.TE
.PP
Total: 512 bytes.
.\"
.\" -------------------------------------------------------------------------
.SH JUMP HEADER (0x000\-0x002)
.\"
A three-byte jump to the actual entry point of the boot code, past the
data area.
Common encodings are
.B EB\ xx\ 90
(short JMP + NOP) and
.B E9\ xx\ xx
(near JMP).
.\"
.\" -------------------------------------------------------------------------
.SH BOOT CODE REGION (0x003\-0x1AF)
.\"
In a standard DOS MBR this entire range is executable machine code.
.B MBR88
uses the low end of this region for boot menu label storage and places
its code above that.
The final byte of
.B MBR88
boot code sits at
.BR 0x1AF.
.SS Boot Menu Label Slots (0x041\-0x080)\ \ [MBR88]
.B MBR88
stores a display label for each partition table entry in four consecutive
16-byte slots beginning at offset
.BR 0x041 .
.PP
.B Slot layout (16 bytes):
.PP
.TS
l l .
Bytes 0\-10	Label text: 1 to 11 printable ASCII characters.
Byte N	Terminator: CR (0x0D), LF (0x0A), or NUL (0x00).
	N is the index of the first terminator byte.
Bytes N+1\-15	Zero padding.
.TE
.PP
A slot is valid if at least one printable ASCII character precedes the
terminator, the terminator is CR, LF, or NUL, and all bytes after the
terminator are zero.
An all-zero slot means no label is set for that partition.
.PP
.B Slot-to-partition mapping:
.PP
.TS
l l .
Slot 0 (0x041\-0x050)	Partition 1
Slot 1 (0x051\-0x060)	Partition 2
Slot 2 (0x061\-0x070)	Partition 3
Slot 3 (0x071\-0x080)	Partition 4
.TE
.\"
.\" -------------------------------------------------------------------------
.SH MBRHDR SIGNATURE REGION (0x1B0\-0x1B7)\ \ [MBR88]
.\"
.TS
l l l .
\fBOffset\fR	\fBSize\fR	\fBDescription\fR
0x1B0	1	Code slack byte.  Always 0x00.
0x1B1	1	Cassini byte.  Always 0xD9.
0x1B2	5	ASCII signature \fBMBR88\fR (0x6D 0x62 0x72 0x38 0x38).
0x1B7	1	Version byte: high nibble = major, low nibble = minor.
	 	MBR88 v0.2 = 0x02.
.TE
.PP
.B The Cassini byte.
.B 0xD9
at offset
.B 0x1B1
is the last byte of telemetry received from the Cassini spacecraft as it
entered Saturn's atmosphere on September 15, 2017.
After
.B 0xD9
arrived, there was no more data.
It is preserved here in memory of the mission.
.\"
.\" -------------------------------------------------------------------------
.SH DISK METADATA REGION (0x1B8\-0x1BD)
.\"
These fields are part of the traditional MBR specification and are
present on any MBR-partitioned disk, not only
.B MBR88
images.
.SS Disk ID (0x1B8\-0x1BB)
A 32-bit little-endian value used by operating systems to track a disk
across reboots and drive letter changes.
Introduced by Windows NT; used by OS/2 and later systems.
.PP
The ID does not need to be cryptographically unique \(em just distinct
enough that two disks on the same machine are unlikely to collide.
A random 32-bit value is fine.
.PP
.B MBR88
leaves this field as
.B 0x00000000
in the template image.
.BR mbrpatch (8)
offers to generate an ID automatically when entering
.B \-n
or
.B \-u
mode if the field is empty.
.PP
.I Display convention:
the disk ID is displayed as four bytes in little-endian order,
matching the convention used by Linux
.BR fdisk (8).
A stored value of
.B DE\ AD\ BE\ EF
displays as
.BR EF\ BE\ AD\ DE .
This surprises people exactly once.
.SS Write-protect Flag (0x1BC\-0x1BD)
A 16-bit hint field introduced alongside the disk ID by Windows NT 3.5.
.B 0x5A5A
indicates the disk should be treated as read-only by compliant tools;
.B 0x0000
is normal (read/write).
DOS 2.0 through 9x left these bytes as zeros by happenstance \(em the
field simply wasn't defined yet.
Even today it is rarely enforced in practice.
.\"
.\" -------------------------------------------------------------------------
.SH PARTITION TABLE (0x1BE\-0x1FD)
.\"
Four 16-byte partition entries packed end-to-end beginning at
.BR 0x1BE .
Each entry describes one primary partition.
Empty slots are all zeros.
.SS Partition Entry Format (16 bytes)
.TS
l l l .
\fBOffset\fR	\fBSize\fR	\fBDescription\fR
0	1	Status byte: 0x00 = inactive, 0x80 = bootable.
1	3	CHS address of the first sector (packed; see below).
4	1	Partition type byte.  See PARTITION TYPE CODES.
5	3	CHS address of the last sector (packed; see below).
8	4	LBA start sector (32-bit little-endian).
12	4	LBA sector count (32-bit little-endian).
.TE
.PP
.BR mbrpatch (8)
computes LBA start and count from the CHS values entered with the
.B g
and
.B n
commands.
XT-class BIOSes use only the CHS fields; the LBA fields are for the
benefit of modern tools.
.SS CHS Encoding (3 bytes, packed)
Cylinder, head, and sector are packed into three bytes in a layout
that manages to hide 10 bits of cylinder across two non-adjacent
bit fields:
.PP
.TS
l l .
Byte 0	Head number (8 bits, 0\-255).
Byte 1 bits 7\-6	High two bits of cylinder number (bits 9\-8).
Byte 1 bits 5\-0	Sector number (6 bits, 1\-63).
Byte 2	Low eight bits of cylinder number (bits 7\-0).
.TE
.PP
Cylinder is 10 bits (0\-1023), head is 8 bits (0\-255), sector is 6
bits (1\-63).
Sector numbers start at 1, not 0.
The IBM XT BIOS uses a subset of this range: typically 0\-305 cylinders,
0\-15 heads, 1\-17 sectors.
.SS Bootable Flag and MBR88
.B MBR88
only displays and chain-loads partitions with status byte
.BR 0x80 .
Unlike conventional single-boot MBR loaders,
.B MBR88
permits more than one partition to be marked bootable simultaneously;
all marked partitions appear in the boot menu.
.PP
Conventional tools such as
.B FDISK
enforce a single active partition.
After running such tools it is necessary to re-run
.B mbrpatch \-p
to restore the bootable flag on any additional boot partitions.
.\"
.\" -------------------------------------------------------------------------
.SH BOOT SIGNATURE (0x1FE\-0x1FF)
.\"
.TS
l l .
0x1FE	0x55
0x1FF	0xAA
.TE
.PP
The BIOS checks for this two-byte signature before treating the sector
as bootable.
.BR mbrpatch (8)
refuses to load files that lack it.
.\"
.\" -------------------------------------------------------------------------
.SH PARTITION TYPE CODES
.\"
The partition type byte at offset 4 of each entry is an informal registry
dating to DOS\ 2.0, assigned by vendors as needed over the decades.
Common values relevant to XT-class hardware:
.PP
.TS
l l .
\fBCode\fR	\fBDescription\fR
00	Empty (slot unused)
01	FAT12
02	Xenix root
03	Xenix usr
04	FAT16 <32\ MB
05	Extended (CHS)
06	FAT16B \(>=32\ MB
07	HPFS / NTFS / exFAT
0A	OS/2 Boot Manager
0B	FAT32
0C	FAT32 LBA
0E	FAT16 LBA
0F	Extended LBA
11	Hidden FAT12
14	Hidden FAT16 <32\ MB
16	Hidden FAT16B
1B	Hidden FAT32
1C	Hidden FAT32 LBA
1E	Hidden FAT16 LBA
64	NetWare 286
80	ELKS / Old MINIX
81	MINIX
82	Linux swap
83	Linux
DB	CP/M-86
EE	GPT protective MBR  (mbrpatch refuses writes to this disk)
EF	EFI system partition
.TE
.PP
Any value 00\-FF is accepted by
.BR mbrpatch (8).
Values not in this table display as
.B Unknown
in the partition summary, but I bet you can find out.
If you know what's on a partition,
.B mbrpatch
won't argue.
.\"
